        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">Weir refers to <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_7951.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Variation</hi></ref> (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-5985.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from J. J. Weir, [before 5] March 1868</ref> and n. 2).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">Canary: <hi rend="italic">Serinus canaria</hi>. See <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_7951.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Variation</hi></ref> 1: 295.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">The serin is <hi rend="italic">Serinus serinus</hi>; the siskin is <hi rend="italic">Spinus spinus</hi>. The serin was recorded to have bred in England from around the middle of the nineteenth century (see <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_5856.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Newton 1893–6</ref>, 3: 829).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">Beachy Head is an area of high chalk cliffs, on the south coast of East Sussex. In <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1966.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Descent</hi></ref> 2: 104, CD cited Weir on the replacement of mates among peregrines.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f5">Weir’s wife has not been further identified.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f6">Weir refers to the common Indian peafowl, <hi rend="italic">Pavo cristatus</hi>; the so-called ‘japanned’ peafowl had been classified as a distinct species, <hi rend="italic">Pavo nigripennis</hi>, by <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_4251.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Philip Lutley Sclater</ref> (Sclater 1860; see also <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1581.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi></ref> vol. 10). In <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_7951.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Variation</hi></ref> 1: 290–2, CD had argued that the japanned peafowl was a variation induced by climate change or reversion to an extinct condition. Both the japanned and the white peafowl are now considered colour variations of <hi rend="italic">Pavo cristatus.</hi></note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f7">The Javan peafowl (now called the green peafowl, <hi rend="italic">Pavo muticus</hi>) does not exhibit the same degree of sexual dimorphism as <hi rend="italic">Pavo cristatus</hi> and female birds have leg-spurs. In <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1966.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Descent</hi></ref> 2: 162–3, CD mentioned the Javan peafowl in his discussion of the development of spurs.</note>
        </div>        
            
